<p>The biggest driver of event ticket sales is social proof — the visible evidence that other people are going and having a great time. Live streaming creates that social proof in real time, and its effects persist long after the event ends in the form of timelapse content and footage archives that drive sales for future events.</p>

<h2>Pre-Event: Using Live Streams to Drive Ticket Sales</h2>

<p>The week before an event is peak conversion time for ticket sales. Live streaming from your venue during setup — stage build, vendor setup, the space coming together — creates genuine anticipation content that performs well on social media and communicates scale and quality to prospective attendees.</p>

<p>An unpolished live stream of your crew hanging lights and sound checks is often more effective than a produced promotional video. It's real. It looks like something worth attending.</p>

<h2>During the Event: Live Streaming the Experience</h2>

<p>A live camera running during your event does several things simultaneously:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Reaches people who didn't buy tickets</strong> — and makes them regret it. This is the FOMO effect that drives future ticket sales.</li>
  <li><strong>Extends the event to a remote audience</strong> — for festivals with geographic pull, out-of-town viewers become future attendees</li>
  <li><strong>Creates a real-time social sharing catalyst</strong> — attendees share the live stream link with their networks, extending your reach</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout">
  <strong>The FOMO loop:</strong> People who watch your event live but didn't attend are the highest-intent audience for your next event. They've already demonstrated interest — they just didn't commit in time. Retargeting this audience for future events is highly effective.
</div>

<h2>Post-Event: The Content That Keeps Working</h2>

<p>Every event you stream with PortOfCams generates a complete timelapse archive — from setup through teardown, covering every moment of the day. This becomes your content library for future event marketing:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Crowd size evidence for sponsor pitches</li>
  <li>Atmosphere footage for future promotional material</li>
  <li>Time-lapse of the crowd building — the most compelling FOMO content</li>
  <li>Setup-to-teardown timelapse — appreciated by vendors and volunteers, shared widely</li>
</ul>

<h2>Multi-Camera Event Coverage</h2>

<p>For larger festivals, multiple camera positions capture different aspects of the event simultaneously. PortOfCams supports multi-camera setups with centralized management. Typical positions for a festival:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Main stage wide shot:</strong> Captures crowd and performer together</li>
  <li><strong>Entry and grounds:</strong> Shows crowd volume and festival atmosphere</li>
  <li><strong>Market/vendor area:</strong> Useful for vendor partnership content</li>
</ul>

<h2>Practical Setup for Day-of Events</h2>

<p>For recurring venues with permanent camera installations, the camera is already in place. For pop-up events in temporary venues, PortOfCams can deploy a mobile camera setup tied to a cellular hotspot. Setup takes under an hour with a pre-configured camera kit. The feed goes live as soon as the camera is online and the service confirms connectivity.</p>

